## Objective
Create the OperatingModelEditor — a document-style editor that shows compiled prose with clickable references.

## Working Directory
`Code&DBs/Workflow/surfaces/app/src/dashboard/`

## Context
The user types natural language. POST /api/compile returns: compiled_prose (string with @/#/{}/agent-name references), references (array of {id, type, slug, span, resolved_to, display_name}), execution_plan (QueueSpec), unresolved (array of strings).

POST /api/commit saves the model to the workflows table.

## Create: `dashboard/OperatingModelEditor.tsx`

Props:
```typescript
interface OperatingModelEditorProps {
  workflowId?: string | null;
  onBack: () => void;
  onCommitted?: (workflowId: string) => void;
}
```

The component has three states:
1. **Input** — user types prose, clicks "Compile"
2. **Review** — shows compiled prose with highlighted references, user can edit
3. **Committed** — saved, showing live execution data

Layout:
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  ← Dashboard                                        [Commit]   │
│                                                                  │
│  ┌─ Title (editable) ──────────────────────────────────────┐   │
│  │  Email Triage                                            │   │
│  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │
│                                                                  │
│  [Input state: textarea]                                        │
│  OR                                                              │
│  [Review state: rendered prose with inline reference badges]    │
│                                                                  │
│  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────  │
│  REFERENCES  (list of resolved/unresolved references)           │
│  EXECUTION PLAN  (list of jobs that will be created)            │
│  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────  │
│  [Compile]  or  [Commit]  or  [Edit]                           │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Input State
- Large textarea with placeholder: "Describe your operating model in plain language..."
- Example text below: "e.g., 'When a support ticket comes in, triage it by priority, check the customer's history, and escalate critical issues within 15 minutes'"
- "Compile" button (amber, primary)

### Review State (after compilation)
- The compiled prose rendered as HTML with reference badges:
  - `@integration/action` → `<span class="ref-badge ref-badge--integration">@gmail/search</span>`
  - `#type/field` → `<span class="ref-badge ref-badge--object">#contact/email</span>`  
  - `{variable}` → `<span class="ref-badge ref-badge--variable">{priority: P1|P2|P3}</span>`
  - `agent-name` → `<span class="ref-badge ref-badge--agent">triage-agent</span>`
- Clicking a badge shows a popover with details (integration info, object schema, etc.)
- Prose is rendered as HTML paragraphs with good typography
- Below the prose:
  - REFERENCES section: list of all references with resolution status (✓ resolved, ⚠ unresolved)
  - EXECUTION PLAN: visual list of jobs that will be created, with agent routes
  - Unresolved warnings if any
- "Edit" button to go back to textarea
- "Commit" button to save

### Committed State
- Same prose view but with a green "LIVE" or "COMMITTED" badge
- Execution metrics section (from useSystemStatus)

### Rendering Compiled Prose

The key function: take the compiled_prose string and the references array, and render it as React elements with clickable badges.

```typescript
function renderCompiledProse(prose: string, references: Reference[]): React.ReactNode {
  // Sort references by span position (descending) to replace from end to start
  const sorted = [...references].sort((a, b) => b.span[0] - a.span[0]);

  // Build segments
  let segments: Array<{ text: string; ref?: Reference }> = [{ text: prose }];

  for (const ref of sorted) {
    const newSegments: typeof segments = [];
    for (const seg of segments) {
      if (seg.ref || !seg.text) {
        newSegments.push(seg);
        continue;
      }
      // Find the reference text in this segment
      const idx = seg.text.indexOf(ref.raw);
      if (idx === -1) {
        newSegments.push(seg);
        continue;
      }
      if (idx > 0) newSegments.push({ text: seg.text.slice(0, idx) });
      newSegments.push({ text: ref.raw, ref });
      const after = seg.text.slice(idx + ref.raw.length);
      if (after) newSegments.push({ text: after });
    }
    segments = newSegments;
  }

  return segments.map((seg, i) => {
    if (seg.ref) {
      return (
        <span
          key={i}
          className={`ref-badge ref-badge--${seg.ref.type}`}
          title={seg.ref.display_name || seg.ref.slug}
          onClick={() => handleRefClick(seg.ref!)}
        >
          {seg.text}
        </span>
      );
    }
    return <span key={i}>{seg.text}</span>;
  });
}
```

